{"title_page": "Weird Comics", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox comic book title|  <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> \n|image=\n|caption=\n|schedule=Monthly\n|format=Anthology\n|publisher=[[Fox Feature Syndicate]]\n|date = Apr. [[1940]] \u2013 Jan. 1942\n|issues=20\n|main_char_team=\n|genre = Superhero\n|writers=\n|artists=\n|pencillers=\n|inkers=\n|letterers=\n|colorists=\n|editors = \n|creative_team_month=\n|creative_team_year=\n|creators=\n\n}}\n'''Weird Comics'''<ref name=gach>{{cite web |url=https://goldenagecomicheroes.wordpress.com/2016/05/19/weird-comics/ |title=Weird Comics   |date=May 19, 2016 |website=Comic Heroes of the Golden Age |access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref> was a [[comic-book]] imprint published by [[Fox Feature Syndicate]] from 1940 to 1942.\n\n''Weird Comics''' characters included Birdman, Sorceress of Zoom, The Dart, [[Thor in comics#Other uses of Thor in comics|Dynamite Thor]], The Eagle, Dynamo and the Black Rider.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Benton |first1=Mike |title=Superhero Comics of the Golden Age: The Illustrated History |date=1992 |publisher=Taylor Publishing Company |location=Dallas |isbn=0-87833-808-X |url=https://archive.org/details/superherocomicso0000bent/page/190 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |page=190}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://comicvine.gamespot.com/weird-comics/4050-31589/\n* http://www.comics.org/series/175/\n\n\n[[Category:1940 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1942 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics titles]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1940]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1942]]\n[[Category:Fox Feature Syndicate]]\n[[Category:Fox Feature Syndicate titles]]\n\n{{Comics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox comic book title|  <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> \n|image=\n|caption=\n|schedule=Monthly\n|format=Anthology\n|publisher=[[Fox Feature Syndicate]]\n|date = Apr. [[1940]] \u2013 Jan. 1942\n|issues=20\n|main_char_team=\n|genre = Superhero\n|writers=\n|artists=\n|pencillers=\n|inkers=\n|letterers=\n|colorists=\n|editors = \n|creative_team_month=\n|creative_team_year=\n|creators=\n\n}}\n'''Weird Comics'''<ref name=gach>{{cite web |url=https://goldenagecomicheroes.wordpress.com/2016/05/19/weird-comics/ |title=Weird Comics   |date=May 19, 2016 |website=Comic Heroes of the Golden Age |access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref> was a [[comic-book]] imprint published by [[Fox Feature Syndicate]] from 1940 to 1942.\n\n''Weird Comics''' characters included Birdman, Sorceress of Zoom, The Dart, [[Thor in comics#Other uses of Thor in comics|Dynamite Thor]], The Eagle, Dynamo and the Black Rider.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Benton |first1=Mike |title=Superhero Comics of the Golden Age: The Illustrated History |date=1992 |publisher=Taylor Publishing Company |location=Dallas |isbn=0-87833-808-X |url=https://archive.org/details/superherocomicso0000bent/page/190 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |page=190}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://comicvine.gamespot.com/weird-comics/4050-31589/\n* http://www.comics.org/series/175/\n\n\n[[Category:1940 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1942 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics titles]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1940]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1942]]\n[[Category:Fox Feature Syndicate]]\n\n{{Comics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rickremember", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weird_Comics"}
{"title_page": "Michael Tearson", "text_new": "{{Infobox presenter\n| name       = Michael Tearson\n| image      = Michael Tearson 1.jpg\n| imagesize  = 200px\n| caption  =  Radio personality, television host, author, wrestler\n| birth_name  = Michael Esterson<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0853612/</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1948}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| show       = Iradiophilly, Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community\n| station    = Plateau\n| network    = \n| timeslot   = Saturday, Sunday Shows and then each as Podcasts Monday to Monday\n| show2      = \n| station2   = 102.9 [[WMGK]] Philadelphia\n| network2   =\n| timeslot2  = Saturday Morning Show\n| style      = Disc Jockey\n| country    = United States\n| prevshow   = Sirius/XM Deep Tracks [[Sirius XM Radio]]\n| parents    =\n| spouse(s)  =\n| children   =\n| web        = {{URL|www.radiothatdoesntsuck.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Tearson''' is an American pioneer underground DJ, concert and special appearance host, author, recording artist and actor. Inducted into the Hall of Fame, 2016, awarded by the Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishexponent.com/headlines/2016/11/blavat-tearson-among-those-honored-by-broadcast-pioneers-of-philadelphia|title=Tearson among those honored by Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia|last=Spikol|first=Liz|date=November 16, 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nDuring the May 1967, while home from his first year of college, Tearson went to the \"15 Below Coffeehouse\" to participate in the talent show.<ref>[http://www.mudcat.org/thread.cfm?threadid=73430 15 Below Coffeehouse, Timonium] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref> \"15 Below Coffeehouse\" was located in Timonium near the Maryland State Fair grounds.<ref>[http://www.marylandstatefair.com/ Maryland State Fair] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref> Before his performance, a very young [[Emmylou Harris]], age 19, made her appearance, taking the audience by surprise with her amazing voice and talent. Not getting noticed for his own performance, Tearson realized that he needed to make a change in his goals. He befriended Emmylou Harris, beginning a lifelong friendship.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.geosound.org/michaeltearson-interview.htm Michael Tearson Interview about his Life] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref>\n\n==Education==\nTearson obtained a bachelor's degree in political science in 1970 from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].\nAs an undergraduate Tearson had his first appearance on the air with WXPN from 1967 to 1970. This was the very first FM Rock shift on WXPN; the show was entitled \"The Attic\".<ref>[http://www.xpn.org/ WXPN University of Pennsylvania] Retrieved 21 May 2011</ref> In January 1970, Tearson joined WDAS-FM Hyski\u2019s Underground as overnighter.<ref>[http://www.hylitradio.com/index.php?page=6  WDAS-FM] Retrieved 21 May 2011</ref>\nTearson has been a longtime member of \"Broadcast Pioneers\",<ref>[http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/ Broadcast Pioneers] retrieved 20 May 2011</ref> and he has been involved with [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] in the United States since its infancy.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>[http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/bp3/michaeltearson.html Broadcast Pioneers with Michael Tearson] Retrieved 19 May 2011</ref>\n\n==1970 to early 1990s==\nIn June 1970, WMMR hired Tearson as a Music Director and weekend disc jockey.  Tearson then moved into the late night personality segment in September 1970 and became a popular on air voice until 1976. Tearson returned two years later to WMMR in 1978 to the 10PM to 2AM time period as \u201cMichael Tearson\u201d. His specialty shows including \u201cPsychedelic Psupper\u201d, \u201cFor Headphones Only\u201d, \u201cThe Import Show\u201d, Import/Export\u201d and \u201cGorilla Theatre\u201d.  Soon after leaving WMMR, in March 1992 Michael Tearson started an on-air show at [[WXPN]], [[Philadelphia Pennsylvania]], which included a free-form hour-long segment called \u201cThe Attic\u201d.\n\n==Late 1990s to early 2000s==\nDuring the late 1990s and early 2000s, he was very diverse in his expertise as a DJ, working to develop special programs for [[WMMR]] with the \u201cA to Z\u201d broadcast and also redeveloped WMMR\u2019s live concert library in the WMMarchives. Both programs are still very popular at the station. He was also involved with [[WXPN]] ''\"Late Nights\"'', which was a diverse and imaginative late-night mix of music. Michael Tearson's studio in his home is called \u201cLynTown Sound\u201d, named after his wife who died from breast cancer on May 10, 1995. The week she died Michael Tearson had an on-air interview scheduled with the band [[Little Feat]] and against the advice of many of his friends, especially Carmen Borrelli, he went on to do the show on Sunday May 14, 1995, before they appeared at Penn\u2019s Landing, in Philadelphia. Tearson is good friends with Little Feat and mentions in an interview with Geosound that they helped him through that difficult time with losing his wife.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> From 1994-1996, Michael Tearson produced and voiced \u201cThe Wall\u201d which was an in-store radio broadcast, at one of their record store chains. In April 2002, [[WMGK]] approached Michael Tearson with an offer to produce a segment for Saturday mornings from 6AM-8AM; it was called \u201cSaturday Morning 60s Show\u201d.<ref>[http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx  Michael Tearson /WMGK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903065303/http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx |date=2011-09-03 }} Retrieved 9June11</ref>\n\nFrom 1999-2003, Michael Tearson was adventurous; he was called Michael \"Mad Dog\" Tearson for a column he wrote on pro wrestling, entitled \u201cOn The Mat\u201d for the Philadelphia Daily News.<ref>[http://www.southjersey.com/articles/index.cfm?articleID=23159 On The Air, Tuning in with radio legend and South Jersey resident Michael Tearson]. October, 2010, Written by Frank Halperin, South Jersey Magazine, Vol 7, Issue 7 Retrieved 9 June 2011</ref> Tearson also writes for two magazines: [[Sing Out!]], a folk song magazine, and The Audiophile Voice.<ref>[http://theaudiophilevoice.com/ The Audiophile Voice Magazine] Retrieved 9 June 2011</ref>\n\n==2000s==\nTearson started at Sirius Radio (Sirius Folk Town) in July 2004-October 2005. He was also the main producer and voice of\n\"The Bob Dylan Radio Hour\" which aired twice on Sundays. Tearson moved to \"Sirius Classic Vinyl\", March 2006-November 2008 which he broadcast Monday through Friday in the afternoons. [[Sirius XM Radio]] was also interested in Michael Tearson and picked him up to work on \"Deep Tracks\" in November 2008.\n\n==2010s and beyond==\nIn July, 2011 Tearson released ''\"Stuff That Works\"'' which was a collaboration of friends that pulled together to create music that Michael Tearson called \"A Philosophy\". An interview by Jonathan Takiff from philly.com on August 24, 2011 captures the enthusiasm of this project that was a dream come true for Tearson.<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-08-24/entertainment/29922475_1_cd-release-robert-hazard-music-writer Radio DJ drops his own tracks] August 24, 2011 By Jonathan Takiff Retrieved 18 September 2011</ref>\nTearson was also interviewed by Jim Six from South Jersey Newspapers. Michael tells Jim Six \u201cThe title of the CD \u201cStuff That Works\u201d is named after a Guy Clark song that isn\u2019t even on the album.\u201d Tearson mentions all who contributed to the CD, which are [[Tom Hampton]], Andy Kravitz, Fran Smith Jr. and Rob Hyman (of [[The Hooters]]), Ted Estersohn, Jay Davidson, Laine Walker Hughes and Lauren Hart.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/gloucestercounty/towns/index.ssf/2011/08/tearson_finds_stuff_that_works.html Tearson finds \u2018Stuff That Works\u2019 for first CD] August 12, 2011 written by Jim Six, South Jersey Newspapers  Retrieved 18 September 2011</ref>\n\nOn October 09, 2011, Kevin Riordan of the Inquirer writes about  Tearson's ''Stuff That Works'' CD release. He interviewed Michael at his home studio, discussing the songs that are on the CD. Michael had said \"The best compliment I've gotten about my album, is that different people pick wildly different songs as their favorite.\" <ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-10-09/news/30260441_1_online-station-neil-diamond-fm Kevin Riordan: Michael Tearson, former WMMR mix maestro, lays tracks of his own] October 09, 2011|By Kevin Riordan, Inquirer Columnist, Retrieved 15 October 2011</ref>\n\nSince April 2002, Tearson produced the weekly 1960s-themed morning show for WMGK, using his expertise and knowledge of [[pop rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[blues rock]] and [[folk rock]], all which can be found in Tearson\u2019s private record library, located at LynTown Sound Studio. On January 15, 2013, WMGK canceled the show.<ref>[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/gizmo/187013276.html#ixzz2I6k6nfsp  Tearson Bites the Dust at WMGK ], January 15, 2013  Retrieved 21 January 2013</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2015, Tearson announced he had departed Sirius/XM Radio after 12 years on the air, soured by corporate tinkering with his program.<ref>[http://mobile.philly.com/blogs/?wss=/philly/blogs/entertainment/music_nightlife/&id=317811221& Philly radio veteran Michael Tearson no longer broadcasting on SiriusXM] Written by Allie Volpe, Retrieved 21 July 2015</ref>\n\nTearson was working with George Manney at Philly Pop Music as the narrator and executive producer for Manney's documentary on Philadelphia's diversified musical community. The project is on hold following the death of Manney in December 2015.<ref>[http://www.phillypopmusic.com/index.html George Manney and Michael Tearson at Philly Pop Music]</ref><ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2015-12-12/news/68963024_1_archivist-michael-tearson-electric-factory, George Manney Dies] By Claire Sasko, Inquirer Staff Writer retrieved 15 March 2016</ref>\n\nTearson also continues to contribute to Radio That Doesn't Suck.<ref>[http://www.rtds.ca Radio That Doesn't Suck]</ref> and at Iradiophilly, Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community on the Plateau channel.<ref>[http://www.iradiophilly.com Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*July 2011, Michael Tearson released first CD, \"Stuff That Works\".\n*Produced and engineered by Andy Kravitz at Sound and Vision Music Productions, Collingswood, NJ.\n*Co-Produced by Michael Tearson and [[Tom Hampton]]<ref>[http://www.tomhampton.com/main.html Tom Hampton] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207131124/http://www.tomhampton.com/main.html |date=2011-02-07 }} Retrieved 30 July 2011</ref>\n*October 2013, \"Ruby's Greatest Hit\"\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n!Year !! Movie-Documentary !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1981\n || ''Blow Out'' || Hawker || Motion Picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1994\n || ''Home of Angels'' || Younger Fisherman  || Motion Picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2002\n|| ''13th Child'' || Mental Patient || Motion Picture\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20141204133452/http://archives.citypaper.net/articles/112698/coverstory.html Glory Days] November 26\u2013December 3, 1998\n*{{IMDb name|0853612}}\n*[http://www.freewebs.com/teejo/argue/tearson.html Michael Tearson Interviews Captain Beefheart]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110903065303/http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx WMGK Shows]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tearson, Michael}}\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Sirius Satellite Radio]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox presenter\n| name       = Michael Tearson\n| image      = Michael Tearson 1.jpg\n| imagesize  = 200px\n| caption  =  Radio personality, television host, author, wrestler\n| birth_name  = Michael Esterson<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0853612/</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1948}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| show       = Iradiophilly, Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community\n| station    = Plateau\n| network    = \n| timeslot   = Saturday, Sunday Shows and then each as Podcasts Monday to Monday\n| show2      = \n| station2   = 102.9 [[WMGK]] Philadelphia\n| network2   =\n| timeslot2  = Saturday Morning Show\n| style      = Disc Jockey\n| country    = United States\n| prevshow   = Sirius/XM Deep Tracks [[Sirius XM Radio]]\n| parents    =\n| spouse(s)  =\n| children   =\n| web        = {{URL|www.radiothatdoesntsuck.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Tearson''' is an American pioneer underground DJ, concert and special appearance host, author, recording artist and actor. Inducted into the Hall of Fame, 2016, awarded by the Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishexponent.com/headlines/2016/11/blavat-tearson-among-those-honored-by-broadcast-pioneers-of-philadelphia|title=Tearson among those honored by Broadcast Pioneers of Philadelphia|last=Spikol|first=Liz|date=November 16, 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nDuring the May 1967, while home from his first year of college, Tearson went to the \"15 Below Coffeehouse\" to participate in the talent show.<ref>[http://www.mudcat.org/thread.cfm?threadid=73430 15 Below Coffeehouse, Timonium] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref> \"15 Below Coffeehouse\" was located in Timonium near the Maryland State Fair grounds.<ref>[http://www.marylandstatefair.com/ Maryland State Fair] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref> Before his performance, a very young [[Emmylou Harris]], age 19, made her appearance, taking the audience by surprise with her amazing voice and talent. Not getting noticed for his own performance, Tearson realized that he needed to make a change in his goals. He befriended Emmylou Harris, beginning a lifelong friendship.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.geosound.org/michaeltearson-interview.htm Michael Tearson Interview about his Life] Retrieved 29 May 2011</ref>\n\n==Education==\nTearson obtained a bachelor's degree in political science in 1970 from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].\nAs an undergraduate Tearson had his first appearance on the air with WXPN from 1967 to 1970. This was the very first FM Rock shift on WXPN; the show was entitled \"The Attic\".<ref>[http://www.xpn.org/ WXPN University of Pennsylvania] Retrieved 21 May 2011</ref> In January 1970, Tearson joined WDAS-FM Hyski\u2019s Underground as overnighter.<ref>[http://www.hylitradio.com/index.php?page=6  WDAS-FM] Retrieved 21 May 2011</ref>\nTearson has been a longtime member of \"Broadcast Pioneers\",<ref>[http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/ Broadcast Pioneers] retrieved 20 May 2011</ref> and he has been involved with [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] in the United States since its infancy.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>[http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/bp3/michaeltearson.html Broadcast Pioneers with Michael Tearson] Retrieved 19 May 2011</ref>\n\n==1970 to early 1990s==\nIn June 1970, WMMR hired Tearson as a Music Director and weekend disc jockey.  Tearson then moved into the late night personality segment in September 1970 and became a popular on air voice until 1976. Tearson returned two years later to WMMR in 1978 to the 10PM to 2AM time period as \u201cMichael Tearson\u201d. His specialty shows including \u201cPsychedelic Psupper\u201d, \u201cFor Headphones Only\u201d, \u201cThe Import Show\u201d, Import/Export\u201d and \u201cGorilla Theatre\u201d.  Soon after leaving WMMR, in March 1992 Michael Tearson started an on-air show at [[WXPN]], [[Philadelphia Pennsylvania]], which included a free-form hour-long segment called \u201cThe Attic\u201d.\n\n==Late 1990s to early 2000s==\nDuring the late 1990s and early 2000s, he was very diverse in his expertise as a DJ, working to develop special programs for [[WMMR]] with the \u201cA to Z\u201d broadcast and also redeveloped WMMR\u2019s live concert library in the WMMarchives. Both programs are still very popular at the station. He was also involved with [[WXPN]] ''\"Late Nights\"'', which was a diverse and imaginative late-night mix of music. Michael Tearson's studio in his home is called \u201cLynTown Sound\u201d, named after his wife who died from breast cancer on May 10, 1995. The week she died Michael Tearson had an on-air interview scheduled with the band [[Little Feat]] and against the advice of many of his friends, especially Carmen Borrelli, he went on to do the show on Sunday May 14, 1995, before they appeared at Penn\u2019s Landing, in Philadelphia. Tearson is good friends with Little Feat and mentions in an interview with Geosound that they helped him through that difficult time with losing his wife.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> From 1994-1996, Michael Tearson produced and voiced \u201cThe Wall\u201d which was an in-store radio broadcast, at one of their record store chains. In April 2002, [[WMGK]] approached Michael Tearson with an offer to produce a segment for Saturday mornings from 6AM-8AM; it was called \u201cSaturday Morning 60s Show\u201d.<ref>[http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx  Michael Tearson /WMGK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903065303/http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx |date=2011-09-03 }} Retrieved 9June11</ref>\n\nFrom 1999-2003, Michael Tearson was adventurous; he was called Michael \"Mad Dog\" Tearson for a column he wrote on pro wrestling, entitled \u201cOn The Mat\u201d for the Philadelphia Daily News.<ref>[http://www.southjersey.com/articles/index.cfm?articleID=23159 On The Air, Tuning in with radio legend and South Jersey resident Michael Tearson]. October, 2010, Written by Frank Halperin, South Jersey Magazine, Vol 7, Issue 7 Retrieved 9 June 2011</ref> Tearson also writes for two magazines: \u201cSing Out\u201d, which is a folk song magazine, and The Audiophile Voice.<ref>[http://theaudiophilevoice.com/ The Audiophile Voice Magazine] Retrieved 9 June 2011</ref>\n\n==2000s==\nTearson started at Sirius Radio (Sirius Folk Town) in July 2004-October 2005. He was also the main producer and voice of\n\"The Bob Dylan Radio Hour\" which aired twice on Sundays. Tearson moved to \"Sirius Classic Vinyl\", March 2006-November 2008 which he broadcast Monday through Friday in the afternoons. [[Sirius XM Radio]] was also interested in Michael Tearson and picked him up to work on \"Deep Tracks\" in November 2008.\n\n==2010s and beyond==\nIn July, 2011 Tearson released ''\"Stuff That Works\"'' which was a collaboration of friends that pulled together to create music that Michael Tearson called \"A Philosophy\". An interview by Jonathan Takiff from philly.com on August 24, 2011 captures the enthusiasm of this project that was a dream come true for Tearson.<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-08-24/entertainment/29922475_1_cd-release-robert-hazard-music-writer Radio DJ drops his own tracks] August 24, 2011 By Jonathan Takiff Retrieved 18 September 2011</ref>\nTearson was also interviewed by Jim Six from South Jersey Newspapers. Michael tells Jim Six \u201cThe title of the CD \u201cStuff That Works\u201d is named after a Guy Clark song that isn\u2019t even on the album.\u201d Tearson mentions all who contributed to the CD, which are [[Tom Hampton]], Andy Kravitz, Fran Smith Jr. and Rob Hyman (of [[The Hooters]]), Ted Estersohn, Jay Davidson, Laine Walker Hughes and Lauren Hart.<ref>[http://www.nj.com/gloucestercounty/towns/index.ssf/2011/08/tearson_finds_stuff_that_works.html Tearson finds \u2018Stuff That Works\u2019 for first CD] August 12, 2011 written by Jim Six, South Jersey Newspapers  Retrieved 18 September 2011</ref>\n\nOn October 09, 2011, Kevin Riordan of the Inquirer writes about  Tearson's ''Stuff That Works'' CD release. He interviewed Michael at his home studio, discussing the songs that are on the CD. Michael had said \"The best compliment I've gotten about my album, is that different people pick wildly different songs as their favorite.\" <ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-10-09/news/30260441_1_online-station-neil-diamond-fm Kevin Riordan: Michael Tearson, former WMMR mix maestro, lays tracks of his own] October 09, 2011|By Kevin Riordan, Inquirer Columnist, Retrieved 15 October 2011</ref>\n\nSince April 2002, Tearson produced the weekly 1960s-themed morning show for WMGK, using his expertise and knowledge of [[pop rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[blues rock]] and [[folk rock]], all which can be found in Tearson\u2019s private record library, located at LynTown Sound Studio. On January 15, 2013, WMGK canceled the show.<ref>[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/gizmo/187013276.html#ixzz2I6k6nfsp  Tearson Bites the Dust at WMGK ], January 15, 2013  Retrieved 21 January 2013</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2015, Tearson announced he had departed Sirius/XM Radio after 12 years on the air, soured by corporate tinkering with his program.<ref>[http://mobile.philly.com/blogs/?wss=/philly/blogs/entertainment/music_nightlife/&id=317811221& Philly radio veteran Michael Tearson no longer broadcasting on SiriusXM] Written by Allie Volpe, Retrieved 21 July 2015</ref>\n\nTearson was working with George Manney at Philly Pop Music as the narrator and executive producer for Manney's documentary on Philadelphia's diversified musical community. The project is on hold following the death of Manney in December 2015.<ref>[http://www.phillypopmusic.com/index.html George Manney and Michael Tearson at Philly Pop Music]</ref><ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2015-12-12/news/68963024_1_archivist-michael-tearson-electric-factory, George Manney Dies] By Claire Sasko, Inquirer Staff Writer retrieved 15 March 2016</ref>\n\nTearson also continues to contribute to Radio That Doesn't Suck.<ref>[http://www.rtds.ca Radio That Doesn't Suck]</ref> and at Iradiophilly, Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community on the Plateau channel.<ref>[http://www.iradiophilly.com Philadelphia's Internet Radio Community]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*July 2011, Michael Tearson released first CD, \"Stuff That Works\".\n*Produced and engineered by Andy Kravitz at Sound and Vision Music Productions, Collingswood, NJ.\n*Co-Produced by Michael Tearson and [[Tom Hampton]]<ref>[http://www.tomhampton.com/main.html Tom Hampton] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207131124/http://www.tomhampton.com/main.html |date=2011-02-07 }} Retrieved 30 July 2011</ref>\n*October 2013, \"Ruby's Greatest Hit\"\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n!Year !! Movie-Documentary !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1981\n || ''Blow Out'' || Hawker || Motion Picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1994\n || ''Home of Angels'' || Younger Fisherman  || Motion Picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2002\n|| ''13th Child'' || Mental Patient || Motion Picture\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20141204133452/http://archives.citypaper.net/articles/112698/coverstory.html Glory Days] November 26\u2013December 3, 1998\n*{{IMDb name|0853612}}\n*[http://www.freewebs.com/teejo/argue/tearson.html Michael Tearson Interviews Captain Beefheart]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110903065303/http://www.wmgk.com/shows/michael-tearson/home.aspx WMGK Shows]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tearson, Michael}}\n[[